1. d4 d5 {[%mdl 32768]} { The move order that leads to the Queen's Gambit Accepted. We avoid the Trompowsky and, after } { 2...dxc4 , which is the start of the QGA, we avoid the Catalan as well. } 
2. c4 dxc4 { I extend a warm and hearty welcome to you in this introduction to my course on the Queen's Gambit Accepted! Here's a brief overview of my journey since my first course on Chessable was published and how my approach has changed so far:

This is my 4th course for Chessable. My first course, A Lifetime Repertoire for White based on 1.d4 focusing on the Catalan, continues to be the course most people know me for. I bring up my first course for a reason. This course, which was created in the final quarter of 2020, reflected my attitude towards my own play at that time. I was still a semi-active and ambitious player. The course was as detailed as it could get, brimming with new ideas in topical theoretical lines.

Fast forward to 2024, I no longer spent a fraction of the time I used to spend on my own play. I have gotten busy with numerous other things, and whilst I still enjoy playing recreationally, my approach towards playing chess has changed. I am 30 years old, and I've realized that the majority of players around this age are in similar circumstances, with a clear priority in life which is not necessarily playing chess professionally.

The story behind my QGA: My course on the Queen's Gambit Accepted is primarily catered towards serving the needs of exactly that set of people. People with limited time, but who still require a reliable opening setup (like myself). I picked up the QGA sometime around the last quarter of 2022, in preparation for playing in the World Rapid & Blitz Championship. Whilst I suffered in the tournament in general, the QGA was one of the openings with which I scored pretty decently.

It later became my main opening in all the CCT (Champions Chess Tour) events, serving me very reliably against all opposition rated between 2500-2900. Then in 2024, I set out to play a few OTB tournaments, and I didn't lose a single game with the QGA. In general my attitude towards teaching and creating courses on Chessable has been all about sharing my findings, which has helped me to help everyone else. When I was pondering about the topic for my next course on Chessable, QGA sort of became the default choice. That is the story of how this course came to be.

Who is the course meant for: It is meant to be a compact course, with a minimal set of lines to know. But at the same time, I have also worked on it extensively over the last three years, and tested it personally against the very best. Therefore, the compactness of this repertoire doesn't come at the cost of quality. It primarily caters for people who are looking for a solid setup against 1.d4, without having to know too many lines.

Having said that, the course can also cater to professionals, as at the time of writing this, there are a lot of new ideas within the QGA which haven't yet become mainstream across all levels. With that, I welcome the readers to start learning the QGA, and have fun! } 
3. Nf3 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gf1c4][%csl Rc4]} { White fundamentally has two different ways to try to recapture the c4-pawn. They are
A) The setups with e3
B) The setups with e4.
With 3.Nf3, White signals intention to go for a setup with e3, which usually leads to positions with less concrete and more strategic play. } ( 3.e4 { This is one of the critical attempts to fight against QGA. The obvious idea is to recapture the pawn on c4. With e4, White also stakes a claim towards controlling the center. However, Black has numerous ways to meet this concrete approach and get comfortable play. } 3...e5 { Challenging White's center immediately. } 4.Nf3 4...Bb4+ { This is going to be the starting point of our chapter on 3.e4. This variation is fairly well known in practice on the elite level. However, that is a minuscule part of the chess populace, and in the rest of the eco-system, the line remains relatively new. It leads to exciting positions with uncompromising play, and I personally enjoy this direction a lot! } ) ( 3.e3 { Apart from 3.e4, this is the other way to try and recapture on c4. However, White generally prefers to start with } ) ( 3.Nf3 { if they intend to continue with e3. This is because starting with } ) ( 3.e3 { offers Black the additional possibility of playing } 3...e5 { . But for our purposes this doesn't make much difference and we will just try to transpose to the lines that arise after 3.Nf3. } ( 3...Nf6 4.Bxc4 e6 5.Nf3 Be7 { And we've transposed to the starting position of the Nf3 mainline chapter. } ) ) Nf6 
4. e3 {[%cal Gf1c4][%csl Rc4]} { With the obvious idea to recapture the pawn on c4. This is the mainline against the QGA. } ( { White can also play } 4.Qa4+ { , which is an attempt to recapture the pawn on c4 with the Queen. Against } ) ( 4.Qa4+ { we play } 4...Nc6 5.Qxc4 Be6 { , concretely exploiting the fact that White has broken one of the fundamental opening principles - bringing the Queen out too early. } ) ( 4.Nc3 { is another serious sideline which leads to an interesting fight after } 4...a6 5.e4 b5 { . White gets compensation for the sacrificed pawn here, but only with very accurate play. White can very easily slip into a worse position with a slight inaccuracy. } ) e6 
5. Bxc4 Be7 ( { This is our little surprise. When I started playing the QGA, the topical line continued } 5...c5 6.O-O { and now Black can choose between two different setups: } 6...Nc6 { or } ( 6...a6 { . This was logical - Black challenges White's center right away. These lines are solid lines and Black equalizes in both directions, but with the caveat that there are tons of lines to know.

The setup with ...Be7, on the other hand, is almost a completely new direction. Of course - historically this move has been played several times. But from the point of view of mainstream theory - this move hasn't yet been taken seriously. } ) ) ( { The credit for popularizing this setup goes to Gukesh. Gukesh started out playing this setup with the move order } 5...a6 6.O-O Be7 { in a couple of games, including an important last-round game against Harikrishna in the Chennai GM 2023. He comfortably drew this game, which ended up securing his qualification to the Candidates.

Gukesh then took his assosciation with QGA further by using this setup, this time with the } ) ( 5...Be7 { move order against Hikaru Nakamura in the all important last round game in the Candidates. Gukesh comfortably drew this game as well, securing his qualification to the World Championship match! My interest in these lines was piqued by how Gukesh was using them in these important games and getting a solid game easily against such world class opponents.

Aside from Gukesh, another top player who uses the QGA from time to time is Anish Giri. He recently played this setup with } ) ( 5...Be7 { in the 2024 Olympiad. I also picked up this line for my personal use, and now - you have it in front of you as well! } ) 
