[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/46061359"]

1. d4 d5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. c4 dxc4 
3. e4 ( { The idea of occupying the center with pawns for central control is a chess concept that has been immortalized since time immemorial. The move } 3.e4 { here is not an exception. It has been played as far back as in 1620!

Having two pawns in the center on e4 and d4 certainly has its advantages. However, } ) ( 3.e4 { is also committal in the sense that once White gets the pawn to e4, there is no going back. This leads to situations where Black can use White's pawns on e4 and d4 to get counter-play against White's center. } ) e5 ( { This is one of the most principled approaches against the 3.e4 setup. Black challenges White's center right away. Back in the 1840's, when the Queen's Gambit Accepted was in the early stages of it's conception, } 3...e5 { was the most popular move. } ) ( { Black has other reasonable moves as well here. The major alternates are } 3...Nf6 { and } ) ( 3...b5 { . I choose } ) ( 3...e5 { in this course, because in recent times I became convinced that Black has a pretty straightforward way to equalize. } ) 
4. Nf3 ( { At some point it became clear for White that this is the way to preserve White's center, although it was not at all clear in the initial games in this variation in the 1840's, where even the best players of the world played } 4.d5 { . } ) Bb4+ ( { As two roads diverge in front of us, this is where we take the road less traveled. } 4...exd4 { is the more often played move. However, in recent times, } ) ( 4...Bb4+ { has surged in popularity. The reason for this is concrete. } 5.Nc3 { is the critical response, and here Black has a strong concrete response in } 5...Nf6 { . } ) 
5. Bd2 ( { This is White's more quiet alternate to } 5.Nc3 { , which, as we shall see, leads to chaotic positions. } ) Bxd2+ { Pretty much the only logical option available. White has two ways to recapture now, both quite possible options. } 
6. Nbxd2 { This signals the intention to keep the Queens on the board. White will take Bxc4 on the next move. White might be a pawn down temporarily, but they will have compensation. } exd4 { We of course take out White's central pawn. Having said that, this is also the only move that prevents us from losing our e5-pawn. } 
7. Bxc4 ( 7.Bxc4 { This is the starting position of the 5.Bd2 variation. White is a pawn down, but ahead in development. The initial aim of White is to meet } 7...Ne7? { with } 8.Ng5 { . This also a theme seen in variations after 5.Nbd2 c3. Black needs to be wary of this, and has to be careful not to allow White a dangerous attack. } ) Nc6 { An important developing move, securing the d4-pawn, and also aiming to meet White's Ng5 with ...Ne5 in the future. It is important to develop our Queenside Knight with ...Nc6 first before developing our Kingside Knight to e7 in this variation. } 
8. O-O { White carries on with their development, which is logical. } Nge7 { We also play logically, following up on our previous move 7...Nc6. We aim to develop rapidly and secure our King. } 
9. Ng5 { White has to go for it. } Ne5 { The point of 7...Nc6. The Knight jumps to e5 to save the f7-pawn and also attack the c4-Bishop. } 
10. Bb3 { White's light-squared Bishop protects itself for the moment, and White also threatens f4 on the next move. } N7c6 ( { Attacking the g5-Knight. } 10...h6 { does the same, but getting the Knight from e7 to c6 is a slight improvement. } ) 
11. f4 { White acts in accordance with their plan. The threat is not so much as to attack the e5-Knight, but more to pile on the pressure on f7. White can follow up the pressure with moves like Qh5 and Ndf3. } Bg4 { We develop the Bishop with a tempo, and also ensure that White's threats of Qh5 and Ndf3 are addressed adequately. This also aids Black towards being able to play ...O-O-O in the future. } 
12. Qe1 ( { This is the alternative to } 12.Bxf7+ { . With } ) ( 12.Qe1 { White does not want to cash in by recapturing the pawn. Instead, White prefers to maintain the tension for as long as they can. However, White won't be able to maintain it for that long in any case. } ) h6 { Evicting the g5-Knight. Once this Knight is gone, there is no initiative for White. } 
13. fxe5 { This obvious capture opens up the f-file and gives White access to the f7-point. } Qxg5 { We recapture the Knight. This ends up getting our King out in the open in the center, but that doesn't worry us for the moment, as we will be able to find alternate ways to secure a safe place for the King. } 
14. Bxf7+ Ke7 
15. Qc1 { Escaping Black's obvious intentions of ...Qe3+ to trade White's Queen, and heading towards c5. } Raf8 { The Rook swings by not just to attack the f7-Bishop, but also to make way for Black's King to come towards c8, in effect artificially castling long.

The line continues on for several more moves in the 3.e4 chapter. As we'll see there [/variation/44528518/#/16/w], White can sacrifice the d2-knight for the initiative, but won't have more than a perpetual. } 
