Having two pawns in the center on e4 and d4 certainly has its advantages. However, } ) ( 3.e4 { is also committal in the sense that once White gets the pawn to e4, there is no going back. This leads to situations where Black can use White's pawns on e4 and d4 to get counter-play against White's center. } ) e5 ( { This is one of the most principled approaches against the 3.e4 setup. Black challenges White's center right away. Back in the 1840's, when the Queen's Gambit Accepted was in the early stages of it's conception, } 3...e5 { was the most popular move. } ) ( { Black has other reasonable moves as well here. The major alternates are } 3...Nf6 { and } ) ( 3...b5 { . I choose } ) ( 3...e5 { in this course, because in recent times I became convinced that Black has a pretty straightforward way to equalize. } ) 
4. Nf3 ( { At some point it became clear for White that this is the way to preserve White's center, although it was not at all clear in the initial games in this variation in the 1840's, where even the best players of the world played } 4.d5 { . } ) Bb4+ ( { As two roads diverge in front of us, this is where we take the road less traveled. } 4...exd4 { is the more often played move. However, in recent times, } ) ( 4...Bb4+ { has surged in popularity. The reason for this is concrete. } 5.Nc3 { is the critical response, and here Black has a strong concrete response in } 5...Nf6 { . } ) 
5. Nc3 ( { The principled response to 4...Bb4+, ensuring that the d4-pawn stays protected. The main alternative - } 5.Bd2 Bxd2+ 6.Qxd2 { - also keeps the d4-pawn protected, but allows the trade of the dark-squared Bishops. } ) Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The point! And not a very obvious point. Black's e5-pawn is currently attacked by the Knight on f3 and by the pawn on d4 at the same time. With } 5...Nf6 { , Black does not intend to capture ...Nxe4 after White's } 6.Nxe5 { , as after } ( 6.Nxe5 { White has the threat of Qa4+ . Instead, the idea is concrete. Black aims for quick development, followed by breaking White's center with ...c5. The positions that arise from this variation can get wild, but in a fun and interesting way. } ) ) 
6. Qa4+ { This is an extremely natural trap to fall into as White. It looks tempting: White double attacks the King and the Bishop simultaneously. I faced this the first time in World Rapid Chess Championship in 2022. I figured my way out, but ended up misplaying later and losing the game. } Nc6 { The only way to protect both King and Bishop. } 
7. d5 { Black's Knight is pinned and it looks like White is winning a piece. Or are they? } Nxe4 { Countering the pin with a pin! } 
8. dxc6 { Of course, White takes the piece. White has already set on a path of no return. } Nxc3 { White takes our Knight, we take White's Knight. Now the white Queen is attacked. } 
9. bxc3 ( { The only move, as } 9.cxb7+ { leads to catastrophic damage for White after } 9...Nxa4+ { . } ) Bxc3+ { We continue with checks. Now we have a double attack against White's King and Rook. The situation is quite tense, however. White is a piece up and is one move away from devastating our position with a discovered check after cxb7+. } 
10. Bd2 { The only move. White doesn't worry about the Rook on a1 at the moment, as White has the threat of cxb7+. } b5! { The key move in the whole variation. This move attacks the Queen with a tempo and also eliminates any potential possibility of a discovered check against Black's King. This move is essential for this variation to work and is one of the reasons why the whole idea of 5...Nf6 is playable. } 
11. Qd1 { The Queen has to protect the a1-Rook in order to minimize White's losses. } Bxa1 { Winning an exchange. White gets two minor pieces in return, but in the balance sheet we still have an excess of three pawns. } 
12. Qxa1 O-O ( 12...O-O { It is important to continue precisely. The e5-pawn cannot be touched by White at the moment: } 13.Qxe5 { would be met by } 13...Re8 { . ` r1bq1rk1/p1p2ppp/2P5/1p2p3/2p5/5N2/P2B1PPP/Q3KB1R w K - 1 13 '  13.Nxe5 would be met by 13...Re8 as well, and White will not be able to get out of that unpleasant pin. } ) 
13. a4 ( 13.a4 { Undermining Black's pawn structure and also exploiting the fact that Black cannot play } 13...a6 { yet due to the pin after } 14.axb5! ) ( { It is important for White to try to play energetically. A modest developing move like } 13.Be2 { would be met by } 13...Bf5 { followed by ...Qd5, with very comfortable play for Black. } ) Bf5 { A powerful move, disregarding all the threats against Black's pawns. The Bishop goes towards d3, from where it will impede White's development by preventing them from being able to castle. } ( { I played } 13...e4 { against GM Batsuren in my World Rapid 2022 game, which turned out to be an extremely poor move strategically and turned the computer's evaluation from -1 to } { +1. The reason why 13...e4 is so bad is because in the absence of Black's dark-squared Bishop, it is important to place Black's pawns on the dark squares. Placing them on light squares, especially the e-pawn, gives White's Knight access to the d4-square and their dark-squared Bishop and Queen free access across the entire long diagonal. } ) 
14. axb5 Bd3 { The Bishop heads towards it's square. White will not be able to castle. The e5-pawn is untouchable due to the pin on the e-file after ...Re8. Black has a big advantage. } 
