3. e4 ( { The idea of occupying the center with pawns for central control is a chess concept that has been immortalized since time immemorial. The move } 3.e4 { here is not an exception. It has been played as far back as in 1620!

Having two pawns in the center on e4 and d4 certainly has its advantages. However, } ) ( 3.e4 { is also committal in the sense that once White gets the pawn to e4, there is no going back. This leads to situations where Black can use White's pawns on e4 and d4 to get counter-play against White's center. } ) e5 ( { This is one of the most principled approaches against the 3.e4 setup. Black challenges White's center right away. Back in the 1840's, when the Queen's Gambit Accepted was in the early stages of it's conception, } 3...e5 { was the most popular move. } ) ( { Black has other reasonable moves as well here. The major alternates are } 3...Nf6 { and } ) ( 3...b5 { . I choose } ) ( 3...e5 { in this course, because in recent times I became convinced that Black has a pretty straightforward way to equalize. } ) 
4. Nf3 ( { At some point it became clear for White that this is the way to preserve White's center, although it was not at all clear in the initial games in this variation in the 1840's, where even the best players of the world played } 4.d5 { . } ) Bb4+ ( { As two roads diverge in front of us, this is where we take the road less traveled. } 4...exd4 { is the more often played move. However, in recent times, } ) ( 4...Bb4+ { has surged in popularity. The reason for this is concrete. } 5.Nc3 { is the critical response, and here Black has a strong concrete response in } 5...Nf6 { . } ) 
5. Nc3 ( { The principled response to 4...Bb4+, ensuring that the d4-pawn stays protected. The main alternative - } 5.Bd2 Bxd2+ 6.Qxd2 { - also keeps the d4-pawn protected, but allows the trade of the dark-squared Bishops. } ) Nf6 ( { The point! And not a very obvious point. Black's e5-pawn is currently attacked by the Knight on f3 and by the pawn on d4 at the same time. With } 5...Nf6 { , Black does not intend to capture ...Nxe4 after White's } 6.Nxe5 { , as after } ( 6.Nxe5 { White has the threat of Qa4+ . Instead, the idea is concrete. Black aims for quick development, followed by breaking White's center with ...c5. The positions that arise from this variation can get wild, but in a fun and interesting way. } ) ) 
6. Nxe5 { This is the principled response. White takes Black's central pawn and boasts an established center with pawns on e4 and d4. } b5 { Defending the c4-pawn, as well preventing any Qa4+ related threats. Now Black's threat is ...Nxe4. } 
7. Bg5 { I feel that this is an important variation. This is another way of defending the e4-pawn, indirectly, by pinning Black's Knight. This was played by GM Kasimdzhanov against GM Stevic in 2022. Surprisingly this hasn't had many followers since, but the 5...Nf6 variation itself hasn't seen that many games in general. } c5 {[%mdl 32768]} { I spent a lot of time here trying to choose between the multiple 0.00 options. After doing my research, I concluded that 7...c5 is the simplest way to equalize. 7...O-O is also quite tempting, just like how we play against 7.f3. However, this line is concretely different, and after } ( 7...O-O { the game goes into a concrete variation after } 8.Be2 c5 9.O-O $5 cxd4 10.Nd5 Be7 11.Nxe7+ Qxe7 12.Qxd4 Rd8 13.Qc3 h6 { and here White has the very interesting piece sacrifice with } 14.Bh5 { . This line keeps going on and on, and I felt that Black would have a lot to remember. } ) ( { Therefore I prefer starting with } 7...c5 { . White won't get time to quickly castle short and get the Knight to d5. The move itself is typical for our setup. We create pressure on the d4-pawn, which in turn also weakens White's hold on the e5-Knight. } ) 
8. dxc5 { White has to respond with dxc5. Any operation with the d-pawn weakens the e5-Knight, which in turn enables us to attack other strategic points in White's position, like the e4-pawn. dxc5 at least takes a pawn and opens the d-file for White's Queen. } Qe7 { Again, the simplest. Black attacks the e5-Knight and c5-pawn simultaneously. This is typical for Black in this setup, and one of the important functions of undermining White's pawn on d4 with ...c5. } 
9. Nf3 { It is probably safest for White to simply retreat the Knight. If White can get Be2 and O-O in, then several parts of Black's position are also underdeveloped. } Nbd7 { A profound move. Let's look at the alternates to understand why we arrive here. } ( { A) Firstly, } 9...Qxe4+ { is met by } 10.Be2 { . We will fall behind in development as the Queen on e4 will be exposed and lose time getting back to safety. } ) ( { B) Secondly, if Black takes } 9...Bxc5 { then White has the option of } 10.e5 { , with the idea of exerting pressure on Black's position due to the pin on Black's Queen. } ) ( { C) } 9...Qxc5 { is the third possibility, but here White gets a slight advantage with the simple } 10.Bxf6 { . Therefore it is clear that it is not a great idea to take the pawns right in front of us. } { Having seen a few variations, it becomes easier to understand the usefulness of 9...Nbd7 . Black intends to take on c5 with ...Nxc5. Another useful function is that it prevents White from playing e5, which is a real threat in a lot of positions due to the pin. } ) 
10. Be2 { White stays consistent with their strategy. White just wants to develop as soon as possible and castle short. } Bb7 ( { Once again, we prioritize our development. The White pawns are all hanging and will continue to hang. It is dangerous to capture with } 10...Nxc5 { for the same reason as mentioned on the previous move: due to } 11.e5 { . } ) ( 10...Bxc5 { will get hit with } 11.Nd5 { , again as mentioned in the previous move. } ) ( 10...Qxc5 { is possible, but we prefer to keep the option of how we capture on c5 flexible. } ) 
11. O-O { White completes their development. The immediate threat is Nxb5, as White moves out of the pin with this move. } Bxc3 { We just eliminate the c3-Knight, which is the piece threatening concrete moves like Nxb5 and Nd5. This is not the only way to play, of course, but I found this the simplest. } 
12. bxc3 O-O { We also complete our development. White's pawn structure is scattered all around. On the other hand, White has the pair of Bishops. This would be a good point to stop in general, but I feel that it might be useful to go a bit deeper as White's next move is more or less forced in my opinion. } 
13. a4 { I think that it is really important for White to strike back and counter-attack this way before Black has time to mop up White's pawns. } a6 ( { The simplest and the most human. } 13...bxa4 { is the other move, which also equalizes all the same. It simply leads to having to know a lot more variations as White has many different ways to continue. Therefore I found } ) ( 13...a6 { simpler. } ) 
14. axb5 axb5 
15. Rb1 { White has to once again weaken and attack Black's pawns before Black mops up the e4 and c5-pawns. Right now, Black's b5-pawn is weak. } Qxc5 ( 15...h6 { is an alternative. Black does recover the pawn sooner or later in various ways, e.g. after } 16.Bxf6 Nxf6 17.Rxb5 Nxe4 { , but it's not clear how Black immmediately gets back the pawn. Therefore I decided on 15...Qxc5, which I felt was a little more natural. } ) 
