9. Rxd1 Bxc5 { This is an equal endgame. Black's major challenge here is to develop their queenside pieces. There are two ways to do this: ...a6 and ...b5, or ...b6. The b8-Knight develops to either c6 or d7 based on circumstances. The Rooks go to d8 and c8. White can of course set problems for Black, preventing Black from being able to complete their objective. But that is true with any position and not just specific to this endgame. } 
10. b3 ( { The obvious alternative to } 10.a3 { . With } ) ( 10.b3 { , White's intention is to develop the Bishop. The drawback of this is that the alternative of a3 and b4 gains more space. Apart from that, it also takes the b3-square away from White's Knight in the future. On the other hand, this is less weakening for White. For example, with the White pawn on b4, Black has ideas like ...a5. } ) Nc6 { We develop the Knight first. Black can either continue with ...b6 or ...a6 and ...b5, depending on what White plays. But we are likelier to continue with ...b6 and ...Bb7. } ( 10...a6 { would be met by } 11.Na4 Ba7 12.Ba3 Re8 13.Nc3 { , with a slight edge for White. ` rnb2rk1/pp3ppp/4pn2/2b5/2B5/1PN1PN2/P4PPP/R1BR2K1 b - - 0 10 '  10...Nbd7 is possible, with the idea of preparing ...a6. But after 11.Bb2 a6 12.Bd3! it's not straightforward for Black to get in ...b5. } ) ( { Therefore, } 10...Nc6 { is the best way forward by process of elimination. We can implement the same idea by starting with } ) ( 10...b6 { followed by ...Nc6. } ) 
11. Bb2 b6 { Black is just one move away from equalizing completely. } 
12. Nb5 { This is the most critical line. The Knight not only eyes the d6-square but also opens up the b2-Bishop, enabling White to play Ne5 in the future. } Bb7 { We continue with our development. } 
13. Nd6 { A logical way of continuing. White forces Black to part with their pair of Bishops. } Bxd6 
14. Rxd6 { White has won the pair of Bishops, but Black has a concrete reply prepared. } Na5 { Going after White's light-squared Bishop. If this Bishop moves, then we intend ...Bd5 to trap White's Rook on d6. } 
15. Be2 { A natural retreat square for the Bishop. } Bd5 $10  {[%cal Ga5b7,Gb7c5][%csl Rd6]} ( 15...Bd5 { Trapping the Rook and aiming for ...Nb7. White will look to eliminate our Knight on f6 with } 16.Bxf6 gxf6 { , freeing the d7-square for the Rook. A likely variation is } 17.Rd7 Nb7 18.Rc7 Nc5 { , followed by ...a5. The Rook on c7 will be traded after ...Rfc8. This position is equal despite Black having a doubled pawn, as White has no practical way to take advantage of it. } ) 
