15. Qg3 { Of course, White doesn't want to trade Queens. Keeping the Queens on increases White's chances of keeping an initiative. } Qd7 { Preparing to secure with the King with ...O-O-O. } 
16. g6 { White attempts to get towards Black's King before it gets secure after castling. However, White doesn't have sufficient time. } O-O-O { Black is on time! } 
17. Rf7 { This attacks the Queen, but it is only one threat. } Qd6 { Offering a Queen trade. Black doesn't lose any pawn as White's g6-pawn will also hang if White takes the g7-pawn. } 
18. Qxd6 ( { The attempt to win the pawn with } 18.Rxg7 Qxg3 19.hxg3 hxg6 20.Rxg6 { doesn't do White much good, as it leaves Black with a clearly better pawn structure and a slightly better endgame. Therefore, White prefers to trade the Queens this way, without getting doubled pawns. } ) Rxd6 
19. gxh7 Rxh7 $10  ( 19...Rxh7 { We have reached an equal endgame. Black intends to continue with ...Rf6 on the next move and neutralize White's active Rook on f7. If White prevents it with } 20.Raf1 { , like Keymer did against MVL in 2024, then Black can respond with } 20...Nd8 21.Re7 Re6 { , eliminating the White Rook this way. This is an improvement over the } { 20...b6 played by MVL in his game. } ) ( 19...Rxh7 20.Nf3 { was tried by Mamedyarov in his game against Dominguez in 2022. Dominguez got a fine position after } 20...Nd8 { , although White eventually went on to win the game. Apart from } ( 20...Nd8 { , } ) ( 20...Rf6 { also works in terms of equalizing. } ) ) 
