Having two pawns in the center on e4 and d4 certainly has its advantages. However, } ) ( 3.e4 { is also committal in the sense that once White gets the pawn to e4, there is no going back. This leads to situations where Black can use White's pawns on e4 and d4 to get counter-play against White's center. } ) e5 ( { This is one of the most principled approaches against the 3.e4 setup. Black challenges White's center right away. Back in the 1840's, when the Queen's Gambit Accepted was in the early stages of it's conception, } 3...e5 { was the most popular move. } ) ( { Black has other reasonable moves as well here. The major alternates are } 3...Nf6 { and } ) ( 3...b5 { . I choose } ) ( 3...e5 { in this course, because in recent times I became convinced that Black has a pretty straightforward way to equalize. } ) 
