1. d4 d5 
2. c4 dxc4 
3. Nf3 ( { This is probably the most prudent way to play against the QGA. This takes the game into more solid waters, compared to the } 3.e4 { direction. With } ) ( 3.Nf3 { , White takes the e5-square under control and signals the intention to continue with 4.e3. } ) ( { White usually begins with 3.Nf3 to go into this direction, because starting with } 3.e3 { allows Black the additional option of } 3...e5 { , which dissolves White's center. } ) Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Black continues with their development. This is by no means the only way to continue. In recent times, } 3...a6 { has also become a move which seems to have many takers. However, I don't like that way of playing, as it seems to me that Black is trying to at most equalize and make a draw. Whilst the QGA is a solid opening, I felt that it would still be worthwhile to go into directions where it is easier for White to get a game if they want to. } ) 
4. e3 e6 
5. Bxc4 Be7 ( { This simple developing move was played as far back as 1847. However, as far as modern theory is concerned, this move was hardly known. } 5...a6 { and } ) ( 5...c5 { are much more well-known ways to continue from this position. The break with ...c5 is included in most lines regardless of what Black plays on the 5th move, in order to create pressure on White's d4-pawn and the center immediately. } ) ( { There is an advantage to playing ...c5 without moving the f8-Bishop. Whenever White takes dxc5, Black can develop the bishop with ...Bxc5 in one go. However, this also allows those endgames after } 5...a6 6.O-O c5 7.dxc5 { . These endgames are fine for Black, but they are not enjoyed much by a lot of club players. } ) ( { After } 5...Be7 { the strategic idea of ...c5 is still very much in play. However, we keep that option flexible. Eventually Black does expand on the Queenside with ...c5, ...a6 and ...b5, and uses the space gained to develop pieces on the Queenside. But we do this at a time of our choice and convenience, based on what White plays.

} ) ( 5...Be7 { caught my attention when Gukesh used the lines after } ) ( 5...a6 6.O-O Be7 $5 { to excellent effect in a few games, including an important game against Harikrishna in Chennai, in a game that sealed his qualification to the Candidates with a solid draw. He took this one step further by refining the line and playing the setup with } ) ( 5...Be7 { against Hikaru Nakamura in an all important game in the final round of the Candidates, sealing his spot for the World Championship match against Ding Liren.

Now you have this } ) ( 5...Be7 { setup in front of you. I myself have played a lot of games after } ) ( 5...a6 6.O-O c5 { and I quite like those lines for Black. My rating performance there is pretty decent. However, those lines give White the choice to spring the first surprise or show their preparation. With } ) ( 5...Be7 { , we spring the first surprise, and I expect this surprise to hold good for a considerable time. } ) 
6. Nc3 { This is how Hikaru responded when he was faced with 5...Be7 fairly unexpectedly over the board. This is one of the reasons why I was sold by this variation. Hikaru's reaction was far from the best challenge that could be posed by White, and I also expect the first reaction of most other White players to be similarly unconvincing. } ( { With } 6.Nc3 { , White improves their control over the e4-square. This gives more strength to ideas like Qe2 and e4-e5, which is one of traditional plans for White in this position. } ) c5 { In general, with the Knight already committed to c3, the break with ...c5 works better for Black, as in the endgames after dxc5 White's Knight is better placed on d2 in a lot of situations. Aside from that, White's intention after Nc3 is already to strengthen White's center with e4. ...c5 is an important move to challenge the dominance of White's center. } 
7. a3 { A useful move, preparing the a2-square for White's light-squared Bishop, and also preparing a possible dxc5 and b4 in the future in case White wants to expand on the Queenside. } ( 7.O-O O-O { transposes to the next variation [/variation/44528559/#/7/b]. } ) O-O { We continue on with our Kingside development first. } 
8. O-O { White also completes their Kingside development. } a6 { By no means the only way to continue as Black, but one I found quite convincing. This is the direction of Gukesh's game against Hikaru. I played similarly in one of my own games later. } 
9. Qe2 ( 9.Qe2 { As I mentioned earlier, this is a typical idea for White in these setups. The idea is to go for dxc5 followed by e4-e5. In case Black takes } 9...cxd4 10.exd4 { , White's Queen is also well placed for the IQP setup, although after 9...cxd4 White also has the option of playing } ( 10.Rd1 { . } ) ) b5 { The point of playing ...a6 on the previous move. } 
10. Ba2 b4 ( { Gukesh played } 10...cxd4 { in his game, followed by } 11.exd4 b4 { . However, } ) ( 10...cxd4 { allows the additional possibility of } 11.Rd1 { . This also leads to an equal position for Black, but starting with ...b4 is just simpler. } ) ( 10...cxd4 11.exd4 b4 12.Ne4 bxa3 13.bxa3 Bb7 $10 { was Nakamura-Gukesh, Candidates, 2024. } ) 
11. axb4 cxb4 
12. Na4 { White's Knight is forced to go away from the center. } a5 $10  { Just gaining space and opening up the possibility of ...Ba6 in the future. Black has equalized comfortably. Black continues with ...Nbd7. The light-squared Bishop can go to a6 or b7. } 
