This position is quite fresh, and we will analyze it deeply. This leads to the potential advantage of our opponent having to deal with the position over the board whilst our preparation is 5-10 moves deeper. We also study a diverse set of positions, from endgames to Isolated Queen Pawn positions to positional pawn sacrifices. I believe that all of these will also enhance the general overall understanding of the student. } 
7. Nc3 { The most popular move in this position, although, in my view, not the most challenging. White develops the Knight towards the center, and this is logical. However, on the other hand, this also loses the flexibility of being able to develop the Knight to d2, which is quite useful for White in certain situations in the QGA. } c5 { This is a common response to Nc3 in the QGA. On one hand, Nc3 enables White to play e4-e5. ...c5 effectively counters White's central expansion. Secondly, in the endgames after dxc5, There are certain situations where White prefers the Knight on d2. } 
8. Qe2 { A typical operation by White in QGA positions. White intends to continue with dxc5 followed by e4-e5. } cxd4 { Countering White's threat of dxc5 and breaking White's center. } 
9. exd4 { This is White's point. They intend to enter into this IQP structure which allows them to get an initiative. } a6 ( { In general Black's aim is to get the Knight to d5, to block White's Isolated pawn, and develop the light-squared Bishop. } 9...Nc6 { is the first move you would look at. However, after } 10.Rd1 Nb4 11.Ne5 Nbd5 12.Rd3 { , White's initiative takes off even before Black is able to touch their light-squared Bishop. } ) 
10. a4 { The default response against Black's ...a6 in such situations. But this comes at the cost of giving up an outpost on b4 for Black's Knight. } Nc6 { Heading towards the outpost on b4. } 
11. Be3 { This has been played quite a bit, even by Magnus Carlsen. The obvious idea is to support the d4-pawn whilst developing the Bishop. But I feel that it commits the place of the Bishop too early (it could instead go to g5 for example) and it also blocks the vision of the Queen on the e-file, which prevents possibilities of sacrifices on e6 or f7. } Nb4 { In accordance with our play in this setup. } 
12. Ne5 { The standard position for White's Knight in this setup. } Bd7 $10  { This is typically how we develop the Queen's Bishop when playing against the IQP. The Bishop either goes to freedom on c6, or goes to e8 from where it defends the f7-point. In this position, the Bishop is likelier to go to c6 and eventually towards d5. Our Rook goes to c8. We will gradually work on bringing our f8-Rook into the game, after we secure the a2-f7 diagonal. } 
