1. d4 d5 
2. c4 dxc4 
3. Nf3 ( { This is probably the most prudent way to play against the QGA. This takes the game into more solid waters, compared to the } 3.e4 { direction. With } ) ( 3.Nf3 { , White takes the e5-square under control and signals the intention to continue with 4.e3. } ) ( { White usually begins with 3.Nf3 to go into this direction, because starting with } 3.e3 { allows Black the additional option of } 3...e5 { , which dissolves White's center. } ) Nf6 ( { Black continues with their development. This is by no means the only way to continue. In recent times, } 3...a6 { has also become a move which seems to have many takers. However, I don't like that way of playing, as it seems to me that Black is trying to at most equalize and make a draw. Whilst the QGA is a solid opening, I felt that it would still be worthwhile to go into directions where it is easier for White to get a game if they want to. } ) 
4. e3 e6 
5. Bxc4 Be7 ( { This simple developing move was played as far back as 1847. However, as far as modern theory is concerned, this move was hardly known. } 5...a6 { and } ) ( 5...c5 { are much more well-known ways to continue from this position. The break with ...c5 is included in most lines regardless of what Black plays on the 5th move, in order to create pressure on White's d4-pawn and the center immediately. } ) ( { There is an advantage to playing ...c5 without moving the f8-Bishop. Whenever White takes dxc5, Black can develop the bishop with ...Bxc5 in one go. However, this also allows those endgames after } 5...a6 6.O-O c5 7.dxc5 { . These endgames are fine for Black, but they are not enjoyed much by a lot of club players. } ) ( { After } 5...Be7 { the strategic idea of ...c5 is still very much in play. However, we keep that option flexible. Eventually Black does expand on the Queenside with ...c5, ...a6 and ...b5, and uses the space gained to develop pieces on the Queenside. But we do this at a time of our choice and convenience, based on what White plays.

} ) ( 5...Be7 { caught my attention when Gukesh used the lines after } ) ( 5...a6 6.O-O Be7 $5 { to excellent effect in a few games, including an important game against Harikrishna in Chennai, in a game that sealed his qualification to the Candidates with a solid draw. He took this one step further by refining the line and playing the setup with } ) ( 5...Be7 { against Hikaru Nakamura in an all important game in the final round of the Candidates, sealing his spot for the World Championship match against Ding Liren.

Now you have this } ) ( 5...Be7 { setup in front of you. I myself have played a lot of games after } ) ( 5...a6 6.O-O c5 { and I quite like those lines for Black. My rating performance there is pretty decent. However, those lines give White the choice to spring the first surprise or show their preparation. With } ) ( 5...Be7 { , we spring the first surprise, and I expect this surprise to hold good for a considerable time. } ) 
