Now you have this } ) ( 5...Be7 { setup in front of you. I myself have played a lot of games after } ) ( 5...a6 6.O-O c5 { and I quite like those lines for Black. My rating performance there is pretty decent. However, those lines give White the choice to spring the first surprise or show their preparation. With } ) ( 5...Be7 { , we spring the first surprise, and I expect this surprise to hold good for a considerable time. } ) 
6. O-O { This is the most natural move for White in this position. } O-O { We also follow suit. This is in line with our strategy when playing 5...Be7.

This position is quite fresh, and we will analyze it deeply. This leads to the potential advantage of our opponent having to deal with the position over the board whilst our preparation is 5-10 moves deeper. We also study a diverse set of positions, from endgames to Isolated Queen Pawn positions to positional pawn sacrifices. I believe that all of these will also enhance the general overall understanding of the student. } 
7. Qe2 { This is the second most popular move in this position. But I considered this as one of the main moves for White. It is a classic idea for White in these QGA setups to meet Black's ...c5 with a dxc5 and e4. 7.Qe2 aims to do exactly that. } c5 { In accordance with Black's typical strategic play in QGA. We break in the center, and in effect, break White's center. } 
8. dxc5 { White stays true to their idea. } Bxc5 { What else? :-) } 
9. e4 { With the idea of e5, gaining space on the Kingside, which will be helpful in aiding White's initiative on the Kingside in the future. } Nc6 { There is no way to prevent White's e5, so we just have to face it. } 
10. Nc3 ( { A sophisticated developing move. As White understands that } 10.e5 { doesn't yield an advantage, this is the next move to consider - a move with which White prepares the e5-advance by already taking control of the d5-square. This is White's most critical try. } ) e5 { This is pretty much the only way to continue as Black. It is important to play ...e5 to physically prevent White from playing e5, and also to open up Black's light-squared Bishop. } 
11. Rd1 ( 11.Rd1 { An useful move for White, attacking the Queen with a tempo, and also provoking our Queen to move to an uncomfortable square. If Black plays } 11...Qe7 { or } ( 11...Qc7 { or } ) ( 11...Qa5 { or } ) ( 11...Qe8 { , White responds with } 12.Bg5 { followed by Nd5 related threats. If Black plays ` r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2b1p3/2B1P3/2N2N2/PP2QPPP/R1BR2K1 b - - 1 11 '  11...Qb6 , White has 12.Na4 , gaining the pair of Bishops.

This is the variation that sets Black the most critical problems in our opening. Therefore we'll go concrete and analyze the position deeply. } ) ) Nd4 { The only move once again, as any move by our Queen puts Black in an unfortunate position. } 
12. Nxd4 exd4 ( { Again, the only move. It is important to retain our dark-squared Bishop. } 12...Bxd4 { is the alternative, and here after } 13.Be3 { White gets a substantial advantage, as they not only manage to capture the weakened d4-pawn soon, but also solve the problem of their Queenside pieces. } ) ( { After } 12...exd4 { , the d4-pawn is supported by the Bishop for now, allowing us to create counter-pressure on White's e4-pawn with something like ...Qe7. There are also tactical threats like ...Bg4, the point being that if White plays f3, then we have various discovered attack options like ...d3+ and ...dxc3+. This tactic is only possible if we keep our dark-squared Bishop on the board. Therefore } ) ( 12...exd4 { is better than } ) ( 12...Bxd4 { . } ) 
13. h3 { An intelligent move by White, simply meeting the threat of ...Bg4. White now threatens to get an advantage by using their long-term strategic advantages. Black's d4-pawn is obviously weak. White can also make further inroads into the position by playing e5 and increasing their central control. } Qe8 ( { This is one of the two ways to equalize, and the more concrete option. After } 13...Qe7 { , White can win a pawn after } 14.Na4 Bd6 15.Rxd4 { . That position is also pretty close to equal. With 13...Qe8, we take control of the a4-square, threatening ...dxc3 and not allowing White to play Na4. } ) 
14. Nd5 ( { This is the only way White can keep the game going without it liquidating too much. } 14.Nb5 { will be met by } 14...Qxe4 { . Meanwhile, after ` r1b1qrk1/pp3ppp/5n2/2b5/2BpP3/2N4P/PP2QPP1/R1BR2K1 w - - 1 14 '  14.Nd5 the move 14...Qxe4 is not possible due to 15.Nxf6+ . 14...Nxe4 is met by 15.Bd3 (to prevent any ...d3 related ideas) followed by Nc7, winning material. } ) Nxd5 { Pretty much the only move. } 
15. Bxd5 { White has a position where White can claim a small strategic edge due to a slightly superior pawn structure. Whilst we acknowledge White's slight superiority long-term, there are other dynamic factors that compensate for our worse structure. } Qe7 { Defending the b7-pawn in order to prepare ...Be6. } 
16. Qb5 { White has to try and keep the pressure on by preventing ...Be6. If Black manages to get the Bishop out and develop, then Black wouldn't have much problems. } a6 { First, we evict the Queen from b5, from where it not only controls the b7-point, but also c5, thereby restricting the freedom of Black's pieces. This is one of the ways to equalize. } ( { The other way is with } 16...Be6 17.Qxb7 Qf6 { , sacrificing a pawn for activity. White will at best be able to go into a pawn up opposite-coloured Bishop endgame. But I didn't find that direction totally convincing, because I didn't find the continuation concrete enough. White can play for two results in those positions for a long time and make Black suffer. } ) 
17. Qb3 { Pretty much the only square from where White's Queen can still keep an eye on the b7-pawn and prevent Black's queenside development. } a5 { A clever way to solve Black's problems. The b7-pawn is under pressure and Black isn't able to develop the light-squared Bishop without sacrificing the b7-pawn. But there is another way: Black chooses to develop the a8-Rook first, getting it out via a6, and eventually towards g6. However, to do this, Black first had to drive the Queen away to b3, to keep the c5-Bishop secure. } 
18. Bf4 { White continues on with their development. White's pieces are well-placed in general, and if Black doesn't get active counter-play, White can rack up a sizeable advantage. Black needs to be precise. } Ra6 { In accordance with our plan. We bring our Rook out. The Rook heads towards g6. We are already quite deep with regard to our opening preparation, But the position does require some precision from Black, and therefore I go deeper to make sure we don't get into trouble as Black. } 
19. Qd3 ( { I feel that this is a sophisticated move, which only becomes clear after looking at the variation after } 19.Rac1 { and understanding Black's counter-play and White's problems in the position. The idea of } ) ( 19.Qd3 { is to meet our intended } 19...Rg6 { with } 20.e5 { followed by Be4. Compared to the position after 19.Rac1, this is a better version for White, as Black doesn't have the counter-play with 21...Be6 like they did in the variation after 19.Rac1 Rg6 20.e5 b6 21.Be4 Be6. } ) Kh8 {[%mdl 32768]} { As far as I understand, this is mostly concrete. The idea is to continue with ...Rg6. ...Kh8 is an useful move in certain concrete lines, as after White plays Be4 we usually sacrifice our exchange and White has Bxg6 and Bxh7+ in certain lines. } ( 19...Kh8 { If White plays } 20.e5 { anyway, preparing for our ...Rg6, then we can change tack with } 20...Be6 21.Be4 f5 { , with a fine position. } ) 
20. Rac1 { A logical developing move. White gets their last piece into action. } Rg6 { In accordance with our plan, diving into the concrete mess. } 
21. e5 { White's main idea against our Rook on g6. } b6 { This is an important point to understand. We calmly defend and secure our Bishop on c5, intending ...f6 or ...f5 on the next move. But the main point is the exchange sacrifice on g6 for White's light-squared Bishop, which is a super deep strategic concept that is very difficult to assess. However, it makes sense once we go into it and understand the variations. } 
22. Be4 f5 ( { Not the only way. } 22...Be6 23.Bxg6 fxg6 { also gives Black full compensation due to our advanage on the light squares. However, this concept with ...f5 is definitely worth learning and the move is objectively stronger in any case. } ) 
23. exf6 { Of course. White accepts the challenge. } Qxf6 ( { The only move. If Black takes } 23...Rgxf6 { then after } 24.Bg5 { White wins an exchange for no compensation. The opening of the f-file leads to a situation where all of Black's pieces are active. } ) 
24. Bxg6 { White again has to continue with the principled line, as anything else allows Black comfortable equality. } Qxf4 { Black is an exchange down for the moment. But Black's initiative on the Kingside is pretty promising and all of Black's pieces are at play. } 
25. Bxh7 { Again, the most logical move. } Bb7! ( { The best way, and a very strong idea! Black has two ways to continue with their initiative. } 25...Qxf2+ { is one possibility. White continues with } 26.Kh1 { , and Black's advantage kind of peters out. } ) ( { The other idea is } 25...Bd6 { , but White is just in time to get away from the attack with } 26.Be4 Qh2+ 27.Kf1 { . } ) ( { Therefore, we start with } 25...Bb7 { . The threat is stronger than the execution! } ) 
26. Rf1 ( { One of the ways to defend the f2-pawn. The other way is } 26.Rc2 { , but that leaves the d1-Rook vulnerable to attack after } 26...Bd6 27.g3 Qf3 { , which forces the exchange of the Queens as Black threatens mate. After } 28.Qxf3 Bxf3 29.Rxd4 Bc5 { , White has to be really careful to not get worse as both White's d4-Rook and h7-Bishop are under attack simultaneously, and White's attempt to defend them with } 30.Rh4 { would be met by } 30...g5 31.Rh6 Kg7 { . } ) Bxg2! ( { It is important to eliminate the g2-pawn, as } 26...Bd6 { is met with } 27.g3 { , now that the f2-pawn is defended. } ) 
27. Kxg2 { The only move. } Bd6 { Threatening checkmate with ...Qh2. } 
28. Qg3 ( { The only way to protect the h2-point, as } 28.Rh1 { would have been met by } 28...Qxf2 { . } ) Qxc1 { The point. Just in time, Black has this tactic which enables us to equalize and justify the entire variation. } 
29. Qxd6 ( 29.Rxc1 Bxg3 { goes into an equal endgame. Therefore White tries to retain their piece by attacking the f8-Rook and not allowing Black enough time to capture White's Bishop on h7. } ) Qg5+ 
30. Kh2 Rd8 { Attacking the d6-Queen and the h7-Bishop simultaneously. } 
31. Qg6 { The only way to protect the h7-Bishop and thereby White's advantage. } Qh4 { The final move in this insanely long variation! Black finally forces White to relinquish the Bishop, securing equality. This was a super long and a line which is very unlikely to happen in practice. However, this is White's best try to get an advantage and therefore the course would be incomplete without adding this analysis.

Against this attempt by White Black had multiple ways to secure equality. I chose one of the most concrete approaches for a couple of reasons. Firstly, as much as possible I tried to avoid positions where White can try and get a small edge and play for two results. The second reason is linked to the first reason, in the sense that White also had to play very accurately to get upto here, and in between, there are a number of ways to play inaccurately and lose. } ( 31...Qh4 { Now White can win a pawn with } 32.Qxb6 { , but after } 32...Kxh7 { , White's King is too unsafe for White to seriously try to win. } ) 
