1. d4 d5 
2. c4 dxc4 
3. Nf3 ( { After } 3.e3 { , the move } 3...e5 { is definitely a viable alternative. But it is simpler to transpose to the known path with } ( 3...Nf6 { . I have aimed for a minimalistic, but solid repertoire that is designed to get you an equal position to play with, with minimum investment of time and energy spent on memorization and repetition.

Play can continue } 4.Bxc4 e6 5.Nc3 Be7 { and now } 6.Nf3 O-O { transposes to the 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 lines. } ) ) ( 3.Qa4+ Nc6 4.Nf3 { also transposes after } 4...Nf6 { to lines with 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Qa4+ that we will examine now. } ) Nf6 
4. Nc3 { This is one of the more aggressive tries by White. Instead of going after the c4-pawn, White decides to stake a claim for control over the center and prioritize that. This is the second most played move in this position after 4.e3, and this is one of the more important variations that a QGA player should know as Black. } a6 { We prepare to defend our c4-pawn. If White is going to take control of the center, we don't also want to allow them to regain the pawn that easily. } 
5. e4 { Having committed to central control with 4.Nc3, White should put their feet on the pedal and go for it. } b5 { With White having a robust center, it is important that we retain our extra pawn. } 
6. e5 { White advances with speed. } Nd5 
7. a4 { White has to strike Black's Queenside and try to recover the pawn before Black has time to develop and consolidate. } e6 ( { Focusing on development. Here } 7...b4 { would just weaken the c4-pawn. White would just take } 8.Nxd5 Qxd5 9.Qc2 { and win back the c4-pawn. } ) ( { The other option is to take } 7...Nxc3 8.bxc3 { , but here also there is no good way to retain the pawn chain on the Queenside. } ) ( 7...Bb7 { is possible but potentially allows } 8.e6 { , leading to unclear play. Therefore, I feel ` rnbqkb1r/2p1pppp/p7/1p1nP3/P1pP4/2N2N2/1P3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq a3 0 7 '  7...e6 is the most secure way to continue as Black in this position. It goes towards completing Black's development, at the cost of returning Black's pawn. } ) 
8. axb5 { White recovers their pawn for the moment. } Bb4 { Developing our Bishop, getting one step closer towards completion of our development. } 
9. Qc2 Nb6 { This is how we keep the c4-pawn secure. } 
10. Qe4 { The Queen heads towards g4, which is in accordance with White's strategy in this variation. This is White's most principled move. This is one of the interesting sidelines against the QGA. When GM Krasenkow needed to win in the second game against a young Praggnandhaa in the World Cup since he lost the first game, this is the line he opted for. } Qd5 ( { Although the White Queen wasn't threatening the a8-Rook, it is important to play this move for concrete reasons. Firstly, something like } 10...O-O { literally walks into the line of fire, as after } 11.Ng5 { White has a serious initiative. Secondly, with the white Queen threatening to swing towards our Kingside, it is important that we are able to organize a counter-attack against White's King in the center. By cleverly using the pin on White's King, the Queen on d5 will go towards a8 and then eventually to a1, to organize this counter-attack. } ) 
11. Qg4 { White has to refuse the trade and keep the Queens on. White's primary strategy is based on White's initiative on the Kingside. Trading Queens would extinguish that instantly. } axb5 
12. Rxa8 Qxa8 
13. Qxg7 { White doesn't have a lot of time. If they don't put their foot on the pedal and go after Black's King, White might not get another chance. } Qa1 {[%mdl 32768]} { Cold-blooded. We just ignore White's threat on our h8-Rook and simply go after White's King. This is an important and precise move, designed to shut down the game with a draw. } ( { Black can also play the same thing after inserting } 13...Bxc3+ 14.bxc3 { and now } 14...Qa1 { . However, after } 15.Qxh8+ Kd7 { , in that position White gets the additional possibility of } 16.Be2 Qxc1+ 17.Bd1 { , keeping the game alive. This is what happened in the Krasenkow-Praggnandhaa, 2021 game, which was won by White. } ) ( { Therefore the immediate } 13...Qa1 { is cleaner and more efficient, as it does not allow White the additional possibility to keep the game going with this Be2 idea. If the young Pragg remembered this nuance back in 2021, he would likely have won his mini-match in two games instead of having to win it in the tie-breaks the way he did. } ) 
14. Qxh8+ { White goes ahead with their main idea. } Kd7 ( 14...Kd7 { White has won a Rook, but their King is under fire. White can defend the c1-Bishop with either } 15.Kd2 { or } ( 15.Kd1 { . } ) ) 
15. Kd1 Bxc3 { The simplest. We now take the Knight so that our Queen has the a4-square for a future perpetual. } 
16. bxc3 Qa4+ $10  ( 16...Qa4+ { Forcing a perpetual. If White plays } 17.Kd2 { , then after } 17...Qa2+ { White is forced to accept a perpetual check. } 18.Ke3 { is too dangerous as after } 18...Nd5+ 19.Ke4 Qc2+ { White actually gets checkmated. } ) ( 16...Qa4+ { If White instead plays } 17.Ke1 { , then Black has multiple ways to draw. One of the simplest ways is by playing } 17...Qa1 { . This is similar to the Krasenkow-Pragg position, except the white King has moved a few times now, and therefore cannot legally castle short any longer. The position is likely heading to a draw. } ) 
