10. Ba2 cxd4 { This deviates from the theoretical part of the course. But the move can hardly be criticized. Gukesh demonstrates the right understanding. } 
11. exd4 { In an IQP positions like this, one of Black's main objectives is to get their Queenside pieces to good squares. Gukesh achieves these objectives with fantastic precision. } b4 {[%csl Rc3]} 
12. Ne4 ( 12.axb4 { would be met by } 12...Nc6 { . The point of 11...b4 was to get the Knight towards b4 with a tempo, and eventually to d5. } ) bxa3 
13. bxa3 Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} 
14. Nc3 Nd5 {[%csl Rd4,Gd5]} { Black has developed a good part of their Queenside, gained space, and has left little time for White to develop any sort of initiative. } 
15. Bd2 Nxc3 { Getting rid of one of White's pieces that can help create an initiative. This trade quells White's initiative even before it starts. } 
16. Bxc3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf6d5]} { Black has completed their Queenside development. By this point, Black is starting to take over control of the game. } 
17. Bb1 Rc8 {[%csl Rc3]} 
18. Bd2 Nf6 {[%cal Gb7f3,Gd8d4][%csl Rd4]} 
19. Bd3 Bxf3 
20. Qxf3 Qxd4 { Now Black has a pawn advantage to substantiate his claim of an advantage. This is textbook play on how to exploit the opponent's IQP. } 
21. Rfd1 Qa4 
22. Qb7 {[%csl Ra6]} Bc5 {[%cal Gf6g4][%csl Rf2]} 
23. Be1 {[%csl Gf2]} a5 
24. Qb5 Qxb5 
25. Bxb5 {[%csl Ra5]} { With this Queen trade White has mitigated most of Black's advantage. White's pair of Bishops will provide full compensation for the pawn in the endgame. } Bb6 {[%csl Ga5]} 
